WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.500 align:middle line:90%


00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:11.424 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:11.424 --> 00:00:12.090 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA GARR: Hi.

00:00:12.090 --> 00:00:15.160 align:middle line:84%
I'm Lisa Garr, host of
Gaiam "Inspirations."

00:00:15.160 --> 00:00:17.690 align:middle line:84%
Wouldn't it be great if you
could work out your brain

00:00:17.690 --> 00:00:19.190 align:middle line:90%
like you work out your body?

00:00:19.190 --> 00:00:20.150 align:middle line:90%
Well, why not?

00:00:20.150 --> 00:00:23.990 align:middle line:84%
Your brain can be exercised like
any other muscle in the body,

00:00:23.990 --> 00:00:26.090 align:middle line:84%
but in the case
of neurofeedback,

00:00:26.090 --> 00:00:29.300 align:middle line:84%
it's like training the
brain to balance itself

00:00:29.300 --> 00:00:31.190 align:middle line:90%
and to self-regulate.

00:00:31.190 --> 00:00:33.570 align:middle line:84%
Neurofeedback is
a brain exercise,

00:00:33.570 --> 00:00:35.130 align:middle line:84%
and that's what
we're exploring today

00:00:35.130 --> 00:00:36.940 align:middle line:90%
with Doctor Siegfried Othmer.

00:00:36.940 --> 00:00:39.320 align:middle line:84%
He's the chief
scientist at the EEG

00:00:39.320 --> 00:00:41.210 align:middle line:90%
Institute in Woodland Hills.

00:00:41.210 --> 00:00:44.460 align:middle line:84%
And Dr. Othmer has been involved
in the development of research

00:00:44.460 --> 00:00:49.400 align:middle line:84%
grade instrumentation for
EEG feedback since 1987.

00:00:49.400 --> 00:00:51.370 align:middle line:84%
You've been doing this
for quite a long time.

00:00:51.370 --> 00:00:52.310 align:middle line:90%
>>DR. SIEGFRIED OTHMER: Right.

00:00:52.310 --> 00:00:53.670 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So tell me a
little bit about how

00:00:53.670 --> 00:00:55.350 align:middle line:84%
you got interested
in neurofeedback

00:00:55.350 --> 00:00:57.830 align:middle line:90%
in the first place.

00:00:57.830 --> 00:01:00.990 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: It was actually
through our son Brian.

00:01:00.990 --> 00:01:05.580 align:middle line:84%
And his problem, even though
he started out normally

00:01:05.580 --> 00:01:10.490 align:middle line:84%
enough in life, became
worse at about age seven

00:01:10.490 --> 00:01:13.890 align:middle line:84%
when a seizure
disorder developed.

00:01:13.890 --> 00:01:17.150 align:middle line:84%
And this is actually
not uncommon

00:01:17.150 --> 00:01:21.580 align:middle line:84%
that children develop seizures
first in that kind of age

00:01:21.580 --> 00:01:22.760 align:middle line:90%
range-- six through eight.

00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:25.170 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Was there any
cause a reason for it, or--

00:01:25.170 --> 00:01:28.040 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: Well, we think it
relates back to birth injury.

00:01:28.040 --> 00:01:29.200 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:01:29.200 --> 00:01:32.940 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: But then it doesn't
actually show up until later.

00:01:32.940 --> 00:01:36.449 align:middle line:84%
In this case, the issue,
however, wasn't just seizures.

00:01:36.449 --> 00:01:38.740 align:middle line:84%
Once the seizures had been
identified, that, of course,

00:01:38.740 --> 00:01:39.690 align:middle line:90%
became the focus.

00:01:39.690 --> 00:01:41.920 align:middle line:84%
But as a matter of fact,
he had behavioral problems

00:01:41.920 --> 00:01:45.600 align:middle line:84%
all over the place, and he was a
very difficult child to manage.

00:01:45.600 --> 00:01:50.160 align:middle line:84%
And the neurologist was,
of course, just interested

00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:51.270 align:middle line:90%
in the seizures.

00:01:51.270 --> 00:01:54.460 align:middle line:84%
But we had to live
with him, and we

00:01:54.460 --> 00:01:56.280 align:middle line:84%
realized the problems
were much bigger.

00:01:56.280 --> 00:02:00.070 align:middle line:84%
He was thrown out of school
for behavioral issues.

00:02:00.070 --> 00:02:01.560 align:middle line:90%
He got into fights and so forth.

00:02:01.560 --> 00:02:07.600 align:middle line:84%
And this was very strange,
because he himself very greatly

00:02:07.600 --> 00:02:09.720 align:middle line:90%
disapproved of his own behavior.

00:02:09.720 --> 00:02:12.940 align:middle line:84%
In other words, he didn't
want to behave that way.

00:02:12.940 --> 00:02:13.440 align:middle line:90%
So--

00:02:13.440 --> 00:02:14.420 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: He didn't understand it.

00:02:14.420 --> 00:02:15.140 align:middle line:90%
He couldn't control it.

00:02:15.140 --> 00:02:15.280 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Didn't understand it.

00:02:15.280 --> 00:02:16.280 align:middle line:90%
We didn't understand it.

00:02:16.280 --> 00:02:17.350 align:middle line:90%
He didn't understand it.

00:02:17.350 --> 00:02:21.030 align:middle line:84%
So very clearly,
his behavior was not

00:02:21.030 --> 00:02:22.950 align:middle line:90%
implementing his intentions.

00:02:22.950 --> 00:02:26.290 align:middle line:84%
In other words, the
behavior was brain based.

00:02:26.290 --> 00:02:28.860 align:middle line:84%
It was sort of a
behavioral eruption,

00:02:28.860 --> 00:02:31.320 align:middle line:84%
if you will, much like
the seizure itself.

00:02:31.320 --> 00:02:37.700 align:middle line:84%
And so we later-- years later--
found out about neurofeedback.

00:02:37.700 --> 00:02:41.010 align:middle line:84%
And that really made a
human being out of him.

00:02:41.010 --> 00:02:44.129 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Did you start to notice
the difference right away?

00:02:44.129 --> 00:02:45.670 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: Yes, within
a few sessions.

00:02:45.670 --> 00:02:52.247 align:middle line:84%
But being skeptical parents,
we didn't acknowledge-- my wife

00:02:52.247 --> 00:02:53.830 align:middle line:84%
and I didn't acknowledge
to each other

00:02:53.830 --> 00:02:58.290 align:middle line:84%
that we were, in fact, seeing
changes until a month into it,

00:02:58.290 --> 00:03:01.010 align:middle line:84%
someone else said,
Brian is different.

00:03:01.010 --> 00:03:02.550 align:middle line:90%
Are you guys doing something?

00:03:02.550 --> 00:03:04.850 align:middle line:84%
Well, I says yes, there's
this thing, neurofeedback,

00:03:04.850 --> 00:03:05.930 align:middle line:90%
we're trying.

00:03:05.930 --> 00:03:08.550 align:middle line:84%
And at that point,
other people--

00:03:08.550 --> 00:03:09.909 align:middle line:90%
it was independent validation.

00:03:09.909 --> 00:03:11.450 align:middle line:84%
Somebody else had
noticed the change,

00:03:11.450 --> 00:03:12.635 align:middle line:90%
so it was OK to talk about.

00:03:12.635 --> 00:03:14.010 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So anything,
though, that

00:03:14.010 --> 00:03:16.930 align:middle line:84%
could help improve the
quality of your lives

00:03:16.930 --> 00:03:19.020 align:middle line:84%
is something that's
worth exploring.

00:03:19.020 --> 00:03:20.974 align:middle line:90%
So if you saw change happening--

00:03:20.974 --> 00:03:21.640 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Right.

00:03:21.640 --> 00:03:23.440 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So it was
worth diving into.

00:03:23.440 --> 00:03:25.397 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: That encouraged
us to continue.

00:03:25.397 --> 00:03:27.230 align:middle line:84%
But that, of course,
was just the beginning.

00:03:27.230 --> 00:03:29.230 align:middle line:84%
The first month just
give us an inkling

00:03:29.230 --> 00:03:31.660 align:middle line:84%
of what, in fact, was
possible with him.

00:03:31.660 --> 00:03:33.240 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So what
was the EEG doing?

00:03:33.240 --> 00:03:35.930 align:middle line:84%
And what is EEG, for
people that don't know?

00:03:35.930 --> 00:03:41.050 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: Well, the EEG is
just the electrical activity

00:03:41.050 --> 00:03:42.590 align:middle line:84%
of the brain that
we happen to be

00:03:42.590 --> 00:03:44.840 align:middle line:84%
able to see when we put
the electrode on the scalp

00:03:44.840 --> 00:03:46.600 align:middle line:84%
and kind of listen
in on the brain.

00:03:46.600 --> 00:03:51.470 align:middle line:84%
So it gives us, in a
sense, some visibility

00:03:51.470 --> 00:03:53.640 align:middle line:90%
into the neuronal dance.

00:03:53.640 --> 00:03:55.805 align:middle line:84%
And the neuronal dance
reflects the good

00:03:55.805 --> 00:03:57.430 align:middle line:84%
and the bad of what
the brain is doing.

00:03:57.430 --> 00:04:00.190 align:middle line:84%
So it can show us
the seizure activity

00:04:00.190 --> 00:04:02.970 align:middle line:84%
and it can show us when
the brain is behaving well.

00:04:02.970 --> 00:04:06.580 align:middle line:84%
And we use that information,
then, to train the brain.

00:04:06.580 --> 00:04:08.880 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Is this the same
thing-- is neurofeedback

00:04:08.880 --> 00:04:11.230 align:middle line:90%
the same as biofeedback?

00:04:11.230 --> 00:04:12.560 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Yes and no.

00:04:12.560 --> 00:04:17.050 align:middle line:84%
Both neurofeedback and
biofeedback-- they both fall

00:04:17.050 --> 00:04:21.269 align:middle line:84%
into the same class of
self-regulation training.

00:04:21.269 --> 00:04:23.550 align:middle line:84%
Neurofeedback just
happens to be biofeedback

00:04:23.550 --> 00:04:25.310 align:middle line:84%
using the EEG--
using brain waves.

00:04:25.310 --> 00:04:27.460 align:middle line:90%
There's a little fancier term--

00:04:27.460 --> 00:04:28.860 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Neuro verses bio?

00:04:28.860 --> 00:04:29.360 align:middle line:90%
There's--

00:04:29.360 --> 00:04:30.570 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Right.

00:04:30.570 --> 00:04:32.146 align:middle line:84%
What had happened
is biofeedback sort

00:04:32.146 --> 00:04:35.500 align:middle line:84%
of came along in the
'70s-- '60s and '70s.

00:04:35.500 --> 00:04:37.690 align:middle line:90%
And it became old hat.

00:04:37.690 --> 00:04:39.870 align:middle line:84%
And then along
came neurofeedback.

00:04:39.870 --> 00:04:43.332 align:middle line:84%
And we wanted to bring
attention to this new thing,

00:04:43.332 --> 00:04:44.790 align:middle line:84%
so we had to call
it something new,

00:04:44.790 --> 00:04:46.090 align:middle line:90%
so we called it neurofeedback.

00:04:46.090 --> 00:04:47.352 align:middle line:90%
It's really biofeedback.

00:04:47.352 --> 00:04:49.060 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So you keep
saying self-regulate,

00:04:49.060 --> 00:04:51.030 align:middle line:84%
which I find a fascinating
term, because it

00:04:51.030 --> 00:04:54.130 align:middle line:84%
means that the brain starts
to become reliant upon itself

00:04:54.130 --> 00:04:56.810 align:middle line:90%
and starts to control itself.

00:04:56.810 --> 00:04:59.580 align:middle line:84%
How does the neurofeedback
teach it to do that?

00:04:59.580 --> 00:05:01.550 align:middle line:90%
Or did I get that right at all?

00:05:01.550 --> 00:05:02.790 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Well, yes.

00:05:02.790 --> 00:05:05.060 align:middle line:84%
The thing is that the
brain is, of course,

00:05:05.060 --> 00:05:07.910 align:middle line:90%
a self-regulating entity, right?

00:05:07.910 --> 00:05:15.620 align:middle line:84%
It controls our activities in
life-- it controls itself--

00:05:15.620 --> 00:05:19.340 align:middle line:84%
all by bootstrapping
its own capacities.

00:05:19.340 --> 00:05:21.650 align:middle line:84%
It has learned
everything it knows.

00:05:21.650 --> 00:05:23.660 align:middle line:84%
So everything that
the brain does,

00:05:23.660 --> 00:05:26.170 align:middle line:84%
it does by virtue
of self-regulation.

00:05:26.170 --> 00:05:29.390 align:middle line:84%
It got there through
learning its own behavior.

00:05:29.390 --> 00:05:32.640 align:middle line:84%
And what we're seeing now
is the shortcomings of that.

00:05:32.640 --> 00:05:36.070 align:middle line:84%
So in case of our son
Brian, the seizure activity,

00:05:36.070 --> 00:05:39.740 align:middle line:84%
that's a failure of that
self-regulatory process.

00:05:39.740 --> 00:05:44.020 align:middle line:84%
The question is, can we then
restore self-regulation?

00:05:44.020 --> 00:05:48.220 align:middle line:84%
Can we enhance the brain's
ability to control itself?

00:05:48.220 --> 00:05:51.220 align:middle line:90%
And the answer is yes, we can.

00:05:51.220 --> 00:05:53.950 align:middle line:84%
So we think of the
brain as naturally

00:05:53.950 --> 00:05:55.107 align:middle line:90%
a self-regulating system.

00:05:55.107 --> 00:05:56.940 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, though
it feels, though-- when

00:05:56.940 --> 00:05:59.760 align:middle line:84%
you have something like
anxiety or depression

00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:02.360 align:middle line:84%
or even out of
control appetite, it

00:06:02.360 --> 00:06:04.714 align:middle line:84%
feels like you're
so out of control

00:06:04.714 --> 00:06:07.005 align:middle line:84%
and that the brain isn't
self-regulating or controlling

00:06:07.005 --> 00:06:08.230 align:middle line:90%
at all.

00:06:08.230 --> 00:06:10.650 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: And now we
understand all those problems

00:06:10.650 --> 00:06:15.000 align:middle line:84%
as failures in self-regulation--
that, indeed, there's not just

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:18.720 align:middle line:84%
the psychological perspective
of you're feeling anxious.

00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:20.510 align:middle line:84%
Yes, there's the
feeling component,

00:06:20.510 --> 00:06:23.520 align:middle line:84%
but if we look at the brain,
the brain is acting up.

00:06:23.520 --> 00:06:28.230 align:middle line:84%
And now that's directly
accessible to us

00:06:28.230 --> 00:06:29.240 align:middle line:90%
through brain training.

00:06:29.240 --> 00:06:31.170 align:middle line:84%
In other words, if
we give the brain

00:06:31.170 --> 00:06:37.240 align:middle line:84%
information about its own
failures to regulate properly,

00:06:37.240 --> 00:06:42.440 align:middle line:84%
it can get itself back into
a state of good regulation.

00:06:42.440 --> 00:06:45.144 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So this is similar
to what happened to me when

00:06:45.144 --> 00:06:46.935 align:middle line:84%
I had-- I had an
accident-- a bike accident

00:06:46.935 --> 00:06:49.680 align:middle line:84%
and I damaged a certain
part of my brain.

00:06:49.680 --> 00:06:53.850 align:middle line:84%
And I noticed-- I found
this out after-- unconscious

00:06:53.850 --> 00:06:57.350 align:middle line:84%
for 30 minutes and left
with the inability to speak,

00:06:57.350 --> 00:07:00.620 align:middle line:90%
which I'm still working on.

00:07:00.620 --> 00:07:02.880 align:middle line:84%
I went to a
neurologist and found

00:07:02.880 --> 00:07:05.010 align:middle line:84%
that there was the
prefrontal cortex of my brain

00:07:05.010 --> 00:07:08.460 align:middle line:84%
that was not responding or
sending the signal back as

00:07:08.460 --> 00:07:11.241 align:middle line:84%
fast as it-- as the
other parts of my brain.

00:07:11.241 --> 00:07:11.740 align:middle line:90%
So--

00:07:11.740 --> 00:07:12.406 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Right.

00:07:12.406 --> 00:07:14.840 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And it was about 20%
of what the rest of my brain

00:07:14.840 --> 00:07:15.790 align:middle line:90%
was doing.

00:07:15.790 --> 00:07:21.209 align:middle line:84%
So the neurologist gave me the
diagnosis-- the determination.

00:07:21.209 --> 00:07:22.750 align:middle line:84%
But the way that I
actually healed it

00:07:22.750 --> 00:07:24.970 align:middle line:90%
was through neurofeedback.

00:07:24.970 --> 00:07:28.600 align:middle line:84%
Can you explain how the
neurofeedback re-stimulated

00:07:28.600 --> 00:07:32.682 align:middle line:90%
or regrew that part of my brain?

00:07:32.682 --> 00:07:34.390 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: Let's use
the word reactivated.

00:07:34.390 --> 00:07:35.510 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:07:35.510 --> 00:07:39.570 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: So it brought--
the nerve feedback exercise

00:07:39.570 --> 00:07:43.180 align:middle line:84%
of just the brain seeing
itself in action brought

00:07:43.180 --> 00:07:46.340 align:middle line:84%
your frontal lobe back
into the conversation

00:07:46.340 --> 00:07:48.610 align:middle line:90%
the way it was supposed to be.

00:07:48.610 --> 00:07:52.590 align:middle line:84%
So we can think of the
brain as almost, by analogy,

00:07:52.590 --> 00:07:57.350 align:middle line:84%
to a team where different team
members have different roles.

00:07:57.350 --> 00:07:59.890 align:middle line:84%
But in this case,
every team member

00:07:59.890 --> 00:08:03.020 align:middle line:84%
is actually a huge
platoon of neurons.

00:08:03.020 --> 00:08:07.050 align:middle line:84%
So you've got these platoons of
neurons having to coordinate.

00:08:07.050 --> 00:08:10.960 align:middle line:84%
And there's some precision
that needs to happen there--

00:08:10.960 --> 00:08:12.469 align:middle line:84%
that if there's
slight mismatches,

00:08:12.469 --> 00:08:15.010 align:middle line:84%
then things aren't talking to
each other the way they should.

00:08:15.010 --> 00:08:17.560 align:middle line:84%
And so in the case
of head injury,

00:08:17.560 --> 00:08:19.975 align:middle line:84%
things are almost
working, but not quite.

00:08:19.975 --> 00:08:20.600 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Nuh-uh.

00:08:20.600 --> 00:08:20.870 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Right?

00:08:20.870 --> 00:08:21.830 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:08:21.830 --> 00:08:23.360 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: But it
doesn't take much.

00:08:23.360 --> 00:08:30.790 align:middle line:84%
It may feel like you've lost a
whole lot, as indeed you did,

00:08:30.790 --> 00:08:33.770 align:middle line:84%
felt like you lost a whole
lot of your former abilities.

00:08:33.770 --> 00:08:37.360 align:middle line:84%
But it didn't take much in
the way of a realignment

00:08:37.360 --> 00:08:38.710 align:middle line:90%
to bring those back.

00:08:38.710 --> 00:08:41.230 align:middle line:84%
Because it's not
like the neurons

00:08:41.230 --> 00:08:43.450 align:middle line:90%
are missing-- missing in action.

00:08:43.450 --> 00:08:48.610 align:middle line:84%
It's just that
they're not playing

00:08:48.610 --> 00:08:49.800 align:middle line:90%
with the rest of the team.

00:08:49.800 --> 00:08:52.740 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That is incredibly
valuable information,

00:08:52.740 --> 00:08:54.990 align:middle line:84%
because most people deal
with brain traumas and brain

00:08:54.990 --> 00:08:57.780 align:middle line:84%
injuries and think this is
their sentence for life.

00:08:57.780 --> 00:09:01.440 align:middle line:84%
And that you can actually
re-stimulate the team

00:09:01.440 --> 00:09:05.070 align:middle line:84%
and those neurons to connect
and reconnect and rebuild

00:09:05.070 --> 00:09:07.870 align:middle line:84%
through neurofeedback
is life giving.

00:09:07.870 --> 00:09:09.620 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: This is where
medicine has been.

00:09:09.620 --> 00:09:13.804 align:middle line:84%
It's basically accepted the
brain malfunctions as a given.

00:09:13.804 --> 00:09:15.720 align:middle line:84%
And we nudge it a little
bit with medications.

00:09:15.720 --> 00:09:19.582 align:middle line:84%
And anything that medications
can't do, we say we can't do.

00:09:19.582 --> 00:09:20.540 align:middle line:90%
And now we say, no, no.

00:09:20.540 --> 00:09:23.770 align:middle line:84%
There's this whole other
avenue available to us

00:09:23.770 --> 00:09:27.990 align:middle line:84%
of brain training-- of just
actually allowing the brain

00:09:27.990 --> 00:09:30.820 align:middle line:90%
to witness its own dance.

00:09:30.820 --> 00:09:33.770 align:middle line:84%
And that allows it to
re-coordinate the dance the way

00:09:33.770 --> 00:09:34.914 align:middle line:90%
it should be.

00:09:34.914 --> 00:09:35.580 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Amazing.

00:09:35.580 --> 00:09:38.200 align:middle line:84%
Now, how many of your
patients-- what percentage would

00:09:38.200 --> 00:09:40.090 align:middle line:90%
you say are children?

