problems, because we're

00:19:24.330 --> 00:19:27.300 align:middle line:84%
dealing with neurons that
play by the same rules

00:19:27.300 --> 00:19:29.880 align:middle line:84%
wherever they are and whatever
function they're serving.

00:19:29.880 --> 00:19:35.590 align:middle line:84%
So we're concerned
with the group activity

00:19:35.590 --> 00:19:40.240 align:middle line:84%
of these neurons--
the group behavior.

00:19:40.240 --> 00:19:44.370 align:middle line:84%
And that happens be
exactly what the EEG shows.

00:19:44.370 --> 00:19:48.570 align:middle line:84%
It shows us when the neurons
are dancing together.

00:19:48.570 --> 00:19:50.750 align:middle line:84%
If they're doing their
own thing-- rogue

00:19:50.750 --> 00:19:53.050 align:middle line:90%
neurons-- we don't see it.

00:19:53.050 --> 00:19:55.790 align:middle line:84%
But the neuronal dance
can get out of control

00:19:55.790 --> 00:19:57.800 align:middle line:90%
and that's what a seizure is.

00:19:57.800 --> 00:19:59.700 align:middle line:84%
The seizure is an
extreme example

00:19:59.700 --> 00:20:02.500 align:middle line:84%
of the neuronal dance
getting out of control.

00:20:02.500 --> 00:20:03.084 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I see.

00:20:03.084 --> 00:20:05.249 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: But short of that,
we see everything else,

00:20:05.249 --> 00:20:07.210 align:middle line:84%
like the anxiety,
depression, and so forth.

00:20:07.210 --> 00:20:13.090 align:middle line:84%
All of that can be seen modeled
in terms of deficiencies

00:20:13.090 --> 00:20:15.790 align:middle line:84%
in the regulation of this
global neuronal dance--

00:20:15.790 --> 00:20:18.630 align:middle line:84%
about 8 and 1/2 billion
parametel neurons

00:20:18.630 --> 00:20:19.890 align:middle line:90%
in the cortex.

00:20:19.890 --> 00:20:20.920 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: My god.

00:20:20.920 --> 00:20:23.690 align:middle line:84%
You did a great job of
explaining something so complex

00:20:23.690 --> 00:20:25.670 align:middle line:84%
and making it very
understandable.

00:20:25.670 --> 00:20:26.500 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:20:26.500 --> 00:20:30.440 align:middle line:84%
In the case of someone who's
a veteran-- a Vietnam vet

00:20:30.440 --> 00:20:34.160 align:middle line:84%
or a war veteran--
who has experienced

00:20:34.160 --> 00:20:38.980 align:middle line:84%
severe shock, seen,
definitely visual trauma,

00:20:38.980 --> 00:20:43.550 align:middle line:84%
and auditory trauma, and
kinesthetic trauma-- that

00:20:43.550 --> 00:20:47.010 align:middle line:84%
registers into so many different
centers of the brain-- can

00:20:47.010 --> 00:20:48.650 align:middle line:84%
you-- and I
understand that you've

00:20:48.650 --> 00:20:53.020 align:middle line:84%
done a program with Dr.
Daniel Amen and PTSD patients.

00:20:53.020 --> 00:20:55.057 align:middle line:90%
How was that effective?

00:20:55.057 --> 00:20:57.140 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: Well, first of
all, the thing to realize

00:20:57.140 --> 00:21:01.260 align:middle line:84%
is that, again, even though
the consequences of trauma

00:21:01.260 --> 00:21:04.210 align:middle line:84%
can be devastating-- just as
was the case with your head

00:21:04.210 --> 00:21:12.120 align:middle line:84%
injury-- we're not talking here
about neurons being destroyed.

00:21:12.120 --> 00:21:14.260 align:middle line:84%
They're, again,
merely dysfunctional.

00:21:14.260 --> 00:21:17.060 align:middle line:84%
And so once again, the
same remedy applies.

00:21:17.060 --> 00:21:19.850 align:middle line:84%
We need to recruit these
neuronal assemblies

00:21:19.850 --> 00:21:22.530 align:middle line:84%
into doing their
proper dance again.

00:21:22.530 --> 00:21:29.240 align:middle line:84%
Now, in trauma
disorders, the problem

00:21:29.240 --> 00:21:34.760 align:middle line:84%
has a certain character which
is that the brain is now

00:21:34.760 --> 00:21:38.440 align:middle line:90%
expecting adverse events.

00:21:38.440 --> 00:21:42.150 align:middle line:84%
It lives in the
trauma condition.

00:21:42.150 --> 00:21:45.840 align:middle line:84%
Even though the person may now
have come home from the war

00:21:45.840 --> 00:21:48.320 align:middle line:84%
zone and is now sitting
on the couch at home,

00:21:48.320 --> 00:21:51.835 align:middle line:84%
that brain is still living
under threat, if you will.

00:21:51.835 --> 00:21:52.460 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Mm-hmm.

00:21:52.460 --> 00:21:56.230 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: So it
cannot calm down.

00:21:56.230 --> 00:22:00.410 align:middle line:84%
And whereas the rest
of us who happen

00:22:00.410 --> 00:22:03.810 align:middle line:84%
to be graced with
functional brains

00:22:03.810 --> 00:22:07.420 align:middle line:84%
live actually out of
very calm states-- that

00:22:07.420 --> 00:22:11.480 align:middle line:84%
is the defining quality
of good brain function.

00:22:11.480 --> 00:22:12.880 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Calm states?

00:22:12.880 --> 00:22:16.037 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: Being able to
operate out of calm states.

00:22:16.037 --> 00:22:17.370 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Operate outside of them?

00:22:17.370 --> 00:22:18.280 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: No.

00:22:18.280 --> 00:22:20.120 align:middle line:90%
That you live in them.

00:22:20.120 --> 00:22:21.560 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, yes.

00:22:21.560 --> 00:22:23.200 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: And you
live in calm states.

00:22:23.200 --> 00:22:24.730 align:middle line:84%
And then do you
do what you must,

00:22:24.730 --> 00:22:26.530 align:middle line:84%
but you immediately
return to calm states.

00:22:26.530 --> 00:22:27.030 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:22:27.030 --> 00:22:27.395 align:middle line:90%
Mm-hmm.

00:22:27.395 --> 00:22:27.760 align:middle line:90%
Mm-hmm.

00:22:27.760 --> 00:22:29.259 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: You don't
live very well--

00:22:29.259 --> 00:22:31.390 align:middle line:84%
you're not very functional
in agitated states.

00:22:31.390 --> 00:22:31.990 align:middle line:90%
Nobody is.

00:22:31.990 --> 00:22:32.585 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:22:32.585 --> 00:22:33.085 align:middle line:90%
Got it.

00:22:33.085 --> 00:22:35.430 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: So you want to
operate out of calm states.

00:22:35.430 --> 00:22:40.360 align:middle line:84%
And so our task for
the traumatized brain

00:22:40.360 --> 00:22:44.810 align:middle line:84%
is to reacquaint the
brain with its calm states

00:22:44.810 --> 00:22:46.705 align:middle line:90%
to which it has lost access.

00:22:46.705 --> 00:22:47.330 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Got it.

00:22:47.330 --> 00:22:50.420 align:middle line:84%
And so then the cortisol
and the stress hormones

00:22:50.420 --> 00:22:51.640 align:middle line:90%
are not releasing.

00:22:51.640 --> 00:22:52.550 align:middle line:90%
You're in a place--

00:22:52.550 --> 00:22:52.690 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Right.

00:22:52.690 --> 00:22:54.148 align:middle line:84%
That'll all settle
down once we get

00:22:54.148 --> 00:22:57.510 align:middle line:84%
the neurons dancing
their normal dance.

00:22:57.510 --> 00:23:00.170 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Can this be
achieved through meditation?

00:23:00.170 --> 00:23:02.670 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: Well,
there is our big hint

00:23:02.670 --> 00:23:04.720 align:middle line:90%
of why this is so powerful.

00:23:04.720 --> 00:23:08.420 align:middle line:84%
I mean, people who relate
to meditation because that's

00:23:08.420 --> 00:23:12.740 align:middle line:84%
so familiar can think
about it in those terms.

00:23:12.740 --> 00:23:17.500 align:middle line:84%
So meditation is a way
of calming the brain.

00:23:17.500 --> 00:23:21.150 align:middle line:84%
And good things happen when
you're not doing anything.

00:23:21.150 --> 00:23:23.400 align:middle line:84%
You're just sitting there
meditating and good things--

00:23:23.400 --> 00:23:24.887 align:middle line:84%
we know good things
happen, right?

00:23:24.887 --> 00:23:25.470 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:23:25.470 --> 00:23:27.011 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: So what
does that tell you?

00:23:27.011 --> 00:23:30.360 align:middle line:84%
That tells you that
deactivating the brain

00:23:30.360 --> 00:23:33.050 align:middle line:84%
is actually, for
certain people, the way

00:23:33.050 --> 00:23:36.310 align:middle line:84%
to back to health-- back to
good mental function, right.

00:23:36.310 --> 00:23:41.860 align:middle line:84%
It's just that with meditation,
it's passive in a sense.

00:23:41.860 --> 00:23:45.170 align:middle line:84%
You're giving your brain--
you're taking obstacles

00:23:45.170 --> 00:23:45.860 align:middle line:90%
out the way.

00:23:45.860 --> 00:23:48.690 align:middle line:84%
And the brain may have the
opportunity to self-heal,

00:23:48.690 --> 00:23:51.000 align:middle line:84%
and it may take that
path, but it may not.

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:52.200 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But you can't
meditate when you're driving

00:23:52.200 --> 00:23:53.765 align:middle line:84%
and when you're having
communication and conversation.

00:23:53.765 --> 00:23:54.030 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:23:54.030 --> 00:23:54.410 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Well, certainly not.

00:23:54.410 --> 00:23:57.080 align:middle line:84%
But even if you give the
brain that opportunity,

00:23:57.080 --> 00:23:58.865 align:middle line:90%
it may not find its way.

00:23:58.865 --> 00:23:59.740 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I understand.

00:23:59.740 --> 00:24:02.590 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: So with neurofeedback
now, it is an active process.

00:24:02.590 --> 00:24:04.090 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It guides
it into that, yes.

00:24:04.090 --> 00:24:08.080 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: Because now--
my wife Sue Othmer, who's

00:24:08.080 --> 00:24:11.760 align:middle line:84%
our chief clinician, she calls
it meditation with handrails.

00:24:11.760 --> 00:24:13.960 align:middle line:84%
So basically, it
guides the process

00:24:13.960 --> 00:24:16.330 align:middle line:84%
by showing the brain--
essentially giving it

00:24:16.330 --> 00:24:19.577 align:middle line:84%
a flashlight to guide
it through its darkness.

00:24:19.577 --> 00:24:20.160 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Great.

00:24:20.160 --> 00:24:22.560 align:middle line:84%
Well, there's a video here
that shows some of the SPECT

00:24:22.560 --> 00:24:25.020 align:middle line:84%
scans that Dr. Othmer
did with Daniel Amen

00:24:25.020 --> 00:24:27.870 align:middle line:90%
to-- with patients with PTSD.

00:24:27.870 --> 00:24:29.194 align:middle line:90%
Take a look at this.

00:24:29.194 --> 00:24:29.860 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:24:29.860 --> 00:24:32.860 align:middle line:84%
>>In connection with
our work with veterans,

00:24:32.860 --> 00:24:34.910 align:middle line:84%
we thought it would
be nice to get

00:24:34.910 --> 00:24:37.380 align:middle line:84%
some of the usual
kind of imagery

00:24:37.380 --> 00:24:40.500 align:middle line:84%
that is now done
on brain function

00:24:40.500 --> 00:24:42.580 align:middle line:84%
in order to document
the progress that we're

00:24:42.580 --> 00:24:45.680 align:middle line:90%
making with neurofeedback.

00:24:45.680 --> 00:24:50.280 align:middle line:84%
So in this connection, we're
working with Dr. Daniel Amen,

00:24:50.280 --> 00:24:54.240 align:middle line:84%
who is known around the
world for this kind of work.

00:24:54.240 --> 00:24:58.890 align:middle line:84%
He's looked at SPECT scans for a
variety of clinical conditions,

00:24:58.890 --> 00:25:02.610 align:middle line:90%
including for PTSD.

00:25:02.610 --> 00:25:05.880 align:middle line:84%
And so when one of our veterans
was willing to do that,

00:25:05.880 --> 00:25:08.110 align:middle line:84%
we sent him down there
for some SPECT imagery,

00:25:08.110 --> 00:25:10.020 align:middle line:90%
down to Newport Beach.

00:25:10.020 --> 00:25:13.080 align:middle line:84%
And after the
neurofeedback, another set.

00:25:13.080 --> 00:25:16.950 align:middle line:84%
And we were just really
struck by the difference

00:25:16.950 --> 00:25:19.040 align:middle line:90%
that we could see in the data.

00:25:19.040 --> 00:25:21.540 align:middle line:84%
Now, we were already
excited about the progress

00:25:21.540 --> 00:25:23.930 align:middle line:84%
that he had been making
in the neurofeedback,

00:25:23.930 --> 00:25:29.410 align:middle line:84%
but it's ever so much better
to see it in real color--

00:25:29.410 --> 00:25:30.650 align:middle line:90%
in living color.

00:25:30.650 --> 00:25:32.440 align:middle line:90%
This shows the SPECT imagery.

00:25:32.440 --> 00:25:35.780 align:middle line:84%
SPECT stands for Single
Photon Emission Computerized

00:25:35.780 --> 00:25:36.900 align:middle line:90%
Tomography.

00:25:36.900 --> 00:25:40.670 align:middle line:84%
And it shows us elevations
in activity level

00:25:40.670 --> 00:25:45.480 align:middle line:84%
up here at the anterior
cingulate cortex,

00:25:45.480 --> 00:25:49.480 align:middle line:84%
at the basal ganglia,
and at the thalamus,

00:25:49.480 --> 00:25:55.720 align:middle line:84%
and a whole lot of activity
back here at the cerebellum.

00:25:55.720 --> 00:26:00.110 align:middle line:84%
And this pattern--
this diamond pattern--

00:26:00.110 --> 00:26:04.400 align:middle line:84%
is the characteristic
pattern that we or Dr. Amen

00:26:04.400 --> 00:26:08.880 align:middle line:84%
expect to see typically in the
case of post traumatic stress

00:26:08.880 --> 00:26:10.010 align:middle line:90%
disorder.

00:26:10.010 --> 00:26:12.460 align:middle line:84%
And this was before
the neurofeedback.

00:26:12.460 --> 00:26:15.620 align:middle line:84%
And here we're
seeing the same brain

00:26:15.620 --> 00:26:19.090 align:middle line:84%
after a number of
neurofeedback sessions.

00:26:19.090 --> 00:26:24.060 align:middle line:84%
So in particular, the
anterior cingulate cortex

00:26:24.060 --> 00:26:26.160 align:middle line:90%
has calmed down significantly.

00:26:26.160 --> 00:26:28.690 align:middle line:84%
The basal ganglia
have calmed down.

00:26:28.690 --> 00:26:31.010 align:middle line:90%
The thalamus is still lively.

00:26:31.010 --> 00:26:34.780 align:middle line:90%
But look at the cerebellum.

00:26:34.780 --> 00:26:38.400 align:middle line:84%
It has just majorly
decreased in activity level.

00:26:38.400 --> 00:26:42.890 align:middle line:84%
And we read that as
being all to the good.

00:26:42.890 --> 00:26:47.050 align:middle line:84%
This is a calmer
brain that is more

00:26:47.050 --> 00:26:50.340 align:middle line:84%
able to control and
regulate its own activity.

00:26:50.340 --> 00:26:52.540 align:middle line:84%
And that's very
much the experience

00:26:52.540 --> 00:26:54.940 align:middle line:84%
that this person
has in his life.

00:26:54.940 --> 00:26:57.260 align:middle line:84%
He's just more in
charge of his life.

00:26:57.260 --> 00:27:00.960 align:middle line:84%
And so the experience
of neurofeedback for him

00:27:00.960 --> 00:27:03.437 align:middle line:84%
has been nothing less
than transformational.

00:27:03.437 --> 00:27:04.270 align:middle line:90%
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:27:04.270 --> 00:27:06.228 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I love that,
because you really showed,

00:27:06.228 --> 00:27:09.372 align:middle line:84%
on the SPECT scan, the areas
that the brain changed.

00:27:09.372 --> 00:27:10.080 align:middle line:90%
You can see this.

00:27:10.080 --> 00:27:12.680 align:middle line:84%
Now, you've been
studying this and working

00:27:12.680 --> 00:27:17.030 align:middle line:84%
with this type of research
grade EEG for such a long time.

00:27:17.030 --> 00:27:20.400 align:middle line:84%
Have you seen that people
are-- that the technology has

00:27:20.400 --> 00:27:22.690 align:middle line:84%
improved in any way
or that it's more

00:27:22.690 --> 00:27:25.720 align:middle line:84%
effective for one thing
rather than another?

00:27:25.720 --> 00:27:28.750 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: Oh,
indeed, the technique

00:27:28.750 --> 00:27:30.347 align:middle line:90%
is still under development.

00:27:30.347 --> 00:27:30.930 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Is it?

00:27:30.930 --> 00:27:31.596 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Right.

00:27:31.596 --> 00:27:35.960 align:middle line:84%
So we have new software coming
out several times a year

00:27:35.960 --> 00:27:37.680 align:middle line:90%
as new ideas are implemented.

00:27:37.680 --> 00:27:39.390 align:middle line:84%
And we're not the
only people who

00:27:39.390 --> 00:27:41.080 align:middle line:90%
are innovating in this field.

00:27:41.080 --> 00:27:44.590 align:middle line:84%
So there are a variety of
neurofeedback techniques

00:27:44.590 --> 00:27:48.760 align:middle line:84%
emerging that have their
individual strengths.

00:27:48.760 --> 00:27:50.720 align:middle line:84%
As a matter of
fact, the strength

00:27:50.720 --> 00:27:54.060 align:middle line:84%
of our particular
method is really

00:27:54.060 --> 00:27:56.220 align:middle line:90%
in application to trauma.

00:27:56.220 --> 00:27:59.500 align:middle line:84%
And if we look at the
picture of mental health

00:27:59.500 --> 00:28:02.680 align:middle line:84%
in the large and just look at
the whole raft of issues that

00:28:02.680 --> 00:28:07.910 align:middle line:84%
afflict people that you
know, so much of that

00:28:07.910 --> 00:28:10.660 align:middle line:84%
is traceable to what
happened to these people

00:28:10.660 --> 00:28:11.940 align:middle line:90%
in early childhood.

00:28:11.940 --> 00:28:14.030 align:middle line:84%
Mental health
professionals know this.

00:28:14.030 --> 00:28:17.480 align:middle line:84%
It's just that they can't
do anything about it.

00:28:17.480 --> 00:28:20.010 align:middle line:84%
They know it, but
what can you do?

00:28:20.010 --> 00:28:24.180 align:middle line:84%
We now, you see, can
do something about it.

00:28:24.180 --> 00:28:27.860 align:middle line:84%
Because when we're reshaping
these neuronal networks,

00:28:27.860 --> 00:28:31.810 align:middle line:84%
we're, in effect, reaching back
to the early childhood history.

00:28:31.810 --> 00:28:32.310 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:28:32.310 --> 00:28:35.920 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: And altering what,
in the life of the child,

00:28:35.920 --> 00:28:40.030 align:middle line:84%
first took a set in the first
couple of years of life.

00:28:40.030 --> 00:28:42.000 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Back to the
imprint period--

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:44.057 align:middle line:84%
in the unconscious mind,
you can access this.

00:28:44.057 --> 00:28:44.640 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Yes.

00:28:44.640 --> 00:28:44.940 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:28:44.940 --> 00:28:45.100 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:28:45.100 --> 00:28:45.800 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: Oh, we're
certainly dealing

00:28:45.800 --> 00:28:46.883 align:middle line:90%
with the unconscious mind.

00:28:46.883 --> 00:28:50.940 align:middle line:84%
We're dealing with very basic
regulatory functions that

00:28:50.940 --> 00:28:52.750 align:middle line:84%
are not really under
our conscious control.

00:28:52.750 --> 00:28:54.170 align:middle line:84%
They're way beneath
consciousness.

00:28:54.170 --> 00:28:55.670 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Are you dealing
with the unconscious mind

00:28:55.670 --> 00:28:57.380 align:middle line:84%
or are you dealing
with the chemicals

00:28:57.380 --> 00:28:59.390 align:middle line:84%
in the brain-- the
actual neurons?

00:28:59.390 --> 00:29:01.140 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: Well, the
chemicals, of course--

00:29:01.140 --> 00:29:04.550 align:middle line:84%
you can talk
chemistry, you can talk

00:29:04.550 --> 00:29:06.610 align:middle line:84%
bio-electric function
and so forth.

00:29:06.610 --> 00:29:08.030 align:middle line:90%
They're inseparable.

00:29:08.030 --> 00:29:10.809 align:middle line:84%
We're talking-- we're
of course talking

00:29:10.809 --> 00:29:12.600 align:middle line:84%
about electrical function
in the brain when

00:29:12.600 --> 00:29:13.780 align:middle line:90%
we're talking about neurons.

00:29:13.780 --> 00:29:14.280 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:29:14.280 --> 00:29:16.680 align:middle line:84%
