00:38:26.430 --> 00:38:29.370 align:middle line:84%
where the brain sees the
journey and the brightness

00:38:29.370 --> 00:38:33.350 align:middle line:84%
and goes through the path
and the brain right now

00:38:33.350 --> 00:38:38.200 align:middle line:84%
is receiving feedback of
a rewarding, pleasurable,

00:38:38.200 --> 00:38:41.454 align:middle line:90%
enjoyable frequency, right?

00:38:41.454 --> 00:38:42.120 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Right.

00:38:42.120 --> 00:38:42.619 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:38:42.619 --> 00:38:45.290 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Then when it starts
to shrink, as it's doing now,

00:38:45.290 --> 00:38:50.130 align:middle line:84%
and your view becomes narrow
and you can't see as much,

00:38:50.130 --> 00:38:52.600 align:middle line:90%
that's a non-rewarding--

00:38:52.600 --> 00:38:55.384 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: Well, a
slight iteration

00:38:55.384 --> 00:38:56.300 align:middle line:90%
on what you're saying.

00:38:56.300 --> 00:38:56.883 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Great.

00:38:56.883 --> 00:38:58.904 align:middle line:90%


00:38:58.904 --> 00:39:00.820 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: In this very
low frequency training,

00:39:00.820 --> 00:39:03.580 align:middle line:84%
we no longer think in
terms of good and bad.

00:39:03.580 --> 00:39:04.370 align:middle line:90%
It simply is.

00:39:04.370 --> 00:39:04.870 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:39:04.870 --> 00:39:06.820 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: This is simply
a modulating signal.

00:39:06.820 --> 00:39:08.990 align:middle line:84%
It's just like high
tides, low tide.

00:39:08.990 --> 00:39:10.840 align:middle line:84%
One isn't better than
the other, right?

00:39:10.840 --> 00:39:13.030 align:middle line:84%
It's just part of
the same phenomenon.

00:39:13.030 --> 00:39:16.290 align:middle line:84%
So we're looking at the ebb
and flow of brain activity

00:39:16.290 --> 00:39:21.265 align:middle line:84%
and it's not easy to assign
goodness or badness to it.

00:39:21.265 --> 00:39:24.150 align:middle line:90%


00:39:24.150 --> 00:39:26.420 align:middle line:84%
If we do this with a
traumatized person,

00:39:26.420 --> 00:39:28.360 align:middle line:84%
yes, there's dysregulation
stuck in there

00:39:28.360 --> 00:39:30.910 align:middle line:84%
somewhere-- reflected
in there somewhere.

00:39:30.910 --> 00:39:33.070 align:middle line:84%
But we don't know the good
part from the bad part.

00:39:33.070 --> 00:39:34.650 align:middle line:90%
It's all wrapped up together.

00:39:34.650 --> 00:39:37.850 align:middle line:84%
So the brain sorts it
out and basically works

00:39:37.850 --> 00:39:40.324 align:middle line:84%
on that signal in
this feedback loop.

00:39:40.324 --> 00:39:41.740 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Is this
what dysregulation

00:39:41.740 --> 00:39:44.850 align:middle line:84%
would look like when it narrows
down and it stops traveling?

00:39:44.850 --> 00:39:46.040 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: You're thinking
good and bad again.

00:39:46.040 --> 00:39:46.380 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I am.

00:39:46.380 --> 00:39:46.720 align:middle line:90%
Mm-hmm.

00:39:46.720 --> 00:39:47.386 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Right.

00:39:47.386 --> 00:39:51.274 align:middle line:84%
No, it just simply-- the signal
is low amplitude right now,

00:39:51.274 --> 00:39:52.940 align:middle line:84%
and a few minutes
later, it'll be large.

00:39:52.940 --> 00:39:54.326 align:middle line:90%
And it simply is.

00:39:54.326 --> 00:39:55.140 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:39:55.140 --> 00:39:59.890 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: But the signal is
guiding the brain's dance,

00:39:59.890 --> 00:40:03.490 align:middle line:84%
and it's sort of informing
the brain-- the brain has

00:40:03.490 --> 00:40:04.790 align:middle line:90%
this a-ha experience.

00:40:04.790 --> 00:40:06.090 align:middle line:90%
It says, oh, that's me.

00:40:06.090 --> 00:40:07.810 align:middle line:90%
That is my dance.

00:40:07.810 --> 00:40:08.680 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I see.

00:40:08.680 --> 00:40:12.610 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: And so the brain
engages with that signal,

00:40:12.610 --> 00:40:15.110 align:middle line:84%
interacts with that
signal, and tries

00:40:15.110 --> 00:40:18.970 align:middle line:84%
to control the signal,
because it realizes

00:40:18.970 --> 00:40:20.770 align:middle line:84%
it's responsible
for that signal.

00:40:20.770 --> 00:40:24.890 align:middle line:84%
So that's the nature
of what this is about.

00:40:24.890 --> 00:40:28.410 align:middle line:84%
And you can think about
this in precise analogy

00:40:28.410 --> 00:40:32.920 align:middle line:84%
to how we work with life itself,
so that when you pick up a rake

00:40:32.920 --> 00:40:37.846 align:middle line:84%
to rake the leaves, your brain
assumes ownership of that rake.

00:40:37.846 --> 00:40:38.740 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Mm-hmm.

00:40:38.740 --> 00:40:41.080 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: Or when you pick
up the tennis racquet,

00:40:41.080 --> 00:40:44.990 align:middle line:84%
the brain immediately
forms a vision

00:40:44.990 --> 00:40:46.410 align:middle line:90%
of where the sweet spot is.

00:40:46.410 --> 00:40:49.290 align:middle line:84%
And you can carry the
tennis racquet around

00:40:49.290 --> 00:40:52.547 align:middle line:84%
and your brain is always
is carrying with it

00:40:52.547 --> 00:40:53.880 align:middle line:90%
the knowledge of the sweet spot.

00:40:53.880 --> 00:40:56.050 align:middle line:84%
It just takes responsibility
for that, right?

00:40:56.050 --> 00:40:56.914 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:40:56.914 --> 00:40:58.830 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: That's just
the way the brain works.

00:40:58.830 --> 00:41:03.070 align:middle line:84%
And when the brain sees its own
dance, it does the same thing.

00:41:03.070 --> 00:41:05.250 align:middle line:90%
It just takes control.

00:41:05.250 --> 00:41:07.910 align:middle line:84%
And that taking
control of that signal

00:41:07.910 --> 00:41:10.707 align:middle line:84%
is the path back
to good regulation.

00:41:10.707 --> 00:41:11.290 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I see.

00:41:11.290 --> 00:41:16.020 align:middle line:84%
So now these programs are
pre-built with a specific ebb

00:41:16.020 --> 00:41:18.270 align:middle line:84%
and flow and rhythms
to them, right?

00:41:18.270 --> 00:41:20.450 align:middle line:84%
But are they
interactive, as well,

00:41:20.450 --> 00:41:26.220 align:middle line:84%
where my brain would be
changing the screen at all?

00:41:26.220 --> 00:41:28.260 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: In various ways, yes.

00:41:28.260 --> 00:41:29.640 align:middle line:90%
We have more complicated games.

00:41:29.640 --> 00:41:32.670 align:middle line:84%
There are sometimes
dozens of variables

00:41:32.670 --> 00:41:37.470 align:middle line:84%
that are being altered in
the game as your EEG changes.

00:41:37.470 --> 00:41:38.304 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Fascinating.

00:41:38.304 --> 00:41:39.803 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: And you're
not even aware,

00:41:39.803 --> 00:41:42.020 align:middle line:84%
at the conscious level, of
all these things going on.

00:41:42.020 --> 00:41:45.220 align:middle line:84%
But because the brain
knows it's doing it,

00:41:45.220 --> 00:41:46.840 align:middle line:90%
it picks up on these things.

00:41:46.840 --> 00:41:49.500 align:middle line:84%
You might ignore them
consciously-- in fact,

00:41:49.500 --> 00:41:51.420 align:middle line:84%
we distract people with
movies-- but there's

00:41:51.420 --> 00:41:54.550 align:middle line:84%
all sorts of things going
on that the brain picks up

00:41:54.550 --> 00:41:56.580 align:middle line:90%
because it's doing it.

00:41:56.580 --> 00:42:00.670 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So it could be just
a scape of an ocean-- ebb

00:42:00.670 --> 00:42:01.800 align:middle line:90%
and flow of an ocean.

00:42:01.800 --> 00:42:03.440 align:middle line:84%
We have a couple
of others in here,

00:42:03.440 --> 00:42:05.670 align:middle line:84%
as well, that you can
show the example of.

00:42:05.670 --> 00:42:09.120 align:middle line:84%
And so in the case
of-- and it depends

00:42:09.120 --> 00:42:11.450 align:middle line:84%
on what the person's
individual like is.

00:42:11.450 --> 00:42:14.660 align:middle line:84%
I resonated with butterflies
on my particular one.

00:42:14.660 --> 00:42:20.436 align:middle line:84%
This one is more of a space,
galaxy type of experience.

00:42:20.436 --> 00:42:21.060 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Yeah.

00:42:21.060 --> 00:42:23.790 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And so there's
things moving in it.

00:42:23.790 --> 00:42:26.330 align:middle line:84%
Now, let me ask you as
we're watching this,

00:42:26.330 --> 00:42:30.200 align:middle line:84%
how does this help with someone
where they have maybe sleep

00:42:30.200 --> 00:42:35.250 align:middle line:84%
issues or they're trying to
prevent themselves from waking

00:42:35.250 --> 00:42:39.370 align:middle line:84%
up in the middle the night,
they have disrupted sleep,

00:42:39.370 --> 00:42:42.870 align:middle line:84%
they have night sweats--
those types of things.

00:42:42.870 --> 00:42:46.600 align:middle line:84%
How would something like this
regulate that in the brain?

00:42:46.600 --> 00:42:49.495 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: Well, it's
the same process.

00:42:49.495 --> 00:42:52.350 align:middle line:90%


00:42:52.350 --> 00:42:56.000 align:middle line:84%
The quality of sleep is
actually a good indicator to us

00:42:56.000 --> 00:42:57.630 align:middle line:90%
whether we're doing our job.

00:42:57.630 --> 00:43:00.890 align:middle line:84%
Because at night,
the brain has the job

00:43:00.890 --> 00:43:04.440 align:middle line:84%
entirely to itself of
carrying you through the night

00:43:04.440 --> 00:43:06.300 align:middle line:84%
and giving you a
good night's sleep.

00:43:06.300 --> 00:43:08.260 align:middle line:84%
In the daytime, there
are things you can do.

00:43:08.260 --> 00:43:11.490 align:middle line:84%
You can have coffee
and so forth.

00:43:11.490 --> 00:43:13.300 align:middle line:90%
You can manipulate your state.

00:43:13.300 --> 00:43:13.800 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:43:13.800 --> 00:43:17.450 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: But at night,
the brain is on its own.

00:43:17.450 --> 00:43:20.840 align:middle line:84%
So that's where we can tell
whether we've done our job.

00:43:20.840 --> 00:43:25.740 align:middle line:84%
So if we have trained the brain
to self-regulate appropriately,

00:43:25.740 --> 00:43:28.260 align:middle line:84%
the first signature
of that success

00:43:28.260 --> 00:43:30.370 align:middle line:90%
will be a good night's sleep.

00:43:30.370 --> 00:43:31.470 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, OK.

00:43:31.470 --> 00:43:33.810 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: So we almost
always ask about

00:43:33.810 --> 00:43:38.770 align:middle line:84%
sleep because it's such a
critical indicator to us

00:43:38.770 --> 00:43:41.630 align:middle line:84%
of where the brain
is going wrong.

00:43:41.630 --> 00:43:43.360 align:middle line:84%
Do you have trouble
going to sleep?

00:43:43.360 --> 00:43:45.120 align:middle line:84%
Do you have trouble
with frequent waking

00:43:45.120 --> 00:43:47.650 align:middle line:84%
and then have trouble
going back to sleep?

00:43:47.650 --> 00:43:49.290 align:middle line:84%
Do you wake up too
early and then--

00:43:49.290 --> 00:43:55.260 align:middle line:84%
all these sorts of
things matter to tell us

00:43:55.260 --> 00:43:57.390 align:middle line:84%
exactly how that brain
needs to be trained.

00:43:57.390 --> 00:43:59.960 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: What about nightmares?

00:43:59.960 --> 00:44:02.395 align:middle line:84%
Can EEG help with
something like nightmares?

00:44:02.395 --> 00:44:03.270 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Yeah, yeah.

00:44:03.270 --> 00:44:06.660 align:middle line:84%
Now, that's another instance
of the brain really going out

00:44:06.660 --> 00:44:07.210 align:middle line:90%
of control.

00:44:07.210 --> 00:44:10.910 align:middle line:84%
Now, it turns out
nightmares are exquisitely

00:44:10.910 --> 00:44:12.850 align:middle line:90%
sensitive to this training.

00:44:12.850 --> 00:44:16.140 align:middle line:84%
So we can basically
categorically say

00:44:16.140 --> 00:44:21.500 align:middle line:84%
that if a person has nightmares,
we haven't done our job yet.

00:44:21.500 --> 00:44:25.270 align:middle line:84%
In other words, we should
get rid of nightmares.

00:44:25.270 --> 00:44:26.680 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:44:26.680 --> 00:44:29.550 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: So very high
success rate for nightmares.

00:44:29.550 --> 00:44:32.190 align:middle line:84%
Now, with veterans, it's
a little bit different.

00:44:32.190 --> 00:44:35.460 align:middle line:84%
We talk about night
terrors there.

00:44:35.460 --> 00:44:37.930 align:middle line:84%
Sorry, not night terrors--
nocturnal flashbacks.

00:44:37.930 --> 00:44:40.080 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, OK.

00:44:40.080 --> 00:44:41.130 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: I misspoke.

00:44:41.130 --> 00:44:42.290 align:middle line:90%
Nocturnal flashbacks.

00:44:42.290 --> 00:44:44.830 align:middle line:84%
And they need to be
distinguished from nightmares.

00:44:44.830 --> 00:44:48.140 align:middle line:84%
So there's both issues
involved with veterans.

00:44:48.140 --> 00:44:51.050 align:middle line:84%
And the nocturnal
flashbacks are a little bit

00:44:51.050 --> 00:44:54.740 align:middle line:84%
like the daytime flashbacks,
but they occur at night.

00:44:54.740 --> 00:44:57.130 align:middle line:84%
The nightmares are
another phenomenon.

00:44:57.130 --> 00:44:59.770 align:middle line:84%
And fortunately, we
can deal with both.

00:44:59.770 --> 00:45:00.580 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Amazing.

00:45:00.580 --> 00:45:02.560 align:middle line:84%
What about pain, when
there's pain that's

00:45:02.560 --> 00:45:05.990 align:middle line:84%
caused from a specific, maybe,
injury-- area in the back

00:45:05.990 --> 00:45:09.820 align:middle line:84%
is inflamed or a
disk is bulging?

00:45:09.820 --> 00:45:12.420 align:middle line:84%
Can this actually help
with the response?

00:45:12.420 --> 00:45:13.800 align:middle line:90%
How does it work with pain?

00:45:13.800 --> 00:45:15.830 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: It's interesting
because in the case

00:45:15.830 --> 00:45:19.040 align:middle line:84%
of chronic pain, we
are often dealing

00:45:19.040 --> 00:45:22.550 align:middle line:90%
with a true physical loss.

00:45:22.550 --> 00:45:23.700 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:45:23.700 --> 00:45:25.190 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: --a true
neuronal loss.

00:45:25.190 --> 00:45:27.680 align:middle line:84%
Here, we've really
who lost something.

00:45:27.680 --> 00:45:32.730 align:middle line:84%
So in the spinal column, there
could be the actual destruction

00:45:32.730 --> 00:45:35.060 align:middle line:90%
of tiny little interneurons.

00:45:35.060 --> 00:45:39.480 align:middle line:84%
And that leaves us with
a limited capability

00:45:39.480 --> 00:45:40.690 align:middle line:90%
of doing anything about it.

00:45:40.690 --> 00:45:42.610 align:middle line:90%
So what is left to us?

00:45:42.610 --> 00:45:46.440 align:middle line:84%
What's left to us is the
judgment that the brain makes

00:45:46.440 --> 00:45:47.570 align:middle line:90%
about that pain--

00:45:47.570 --> 00:45:48.070 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:45:48.070 --> 00:45:50.111 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: --which it's
still in charge of, right?

00:45:50.111 --> 00:45:51.947 align:middle line:84%
The messages are coming
up and saying pain.

00:45:51.947 --> 00:45:52.530 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:45:52.530 --> 00:45:53.904 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: But the
brain can still

00:45:53.904 --> 00:45:59.920 align:middle line:84%
choose how to alert you
to that state of pain.

00:45:59.920 --> 00:46:01.520 align:middle line:90%
That's still modulatable.

00:46:01.520 --> 00:46:06.520 align:middle line:84%
And so that central
mechanism of pain regulation

00:46:06.520 --> 00:46:08.150 align:middle line:90%
is still available to us.

00:46:08.150 --> 00:46:13.100 align:middle line:84%
So we can help with chronic pain
even in the most extreme cases.

00:46:13.100 --> 00:46:17.457 align:middle line:84%
Now, how far we can go with
that, that's a broad spectrum.

00:46:17.457 --> 00:46:18.040 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:46:18.040 --> 00:46:22.710 align:middle line:84%
You need to be safe because
if it's a major source of pain

00:46:22.710 --> 00:46:25.741 align:middle line:84%
because something is
severely injured, then

00:46:25.741 --> 00:46:27.740 align:middle line:84%
you don't want to cut the
signal off completely,

00:46:27.740 --> 00:46:29.600 align:middle line:84%
because the body's trying
to tell the brain something,

00:46:29.600 --> 00:46:30.120 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:46:30.120 --> 00:46:32.760 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: The signal is
always still coming up.

00:46:32.760 --> 00:46:33.380 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:46:33.380 --> 00:46:34.504 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: The question is--

00:46:34.504 --> 00:46:35.090 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:46:35.090 --> 00:46:36.420 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: The question
is, what assignment

00:46:36.420 --> 00:46:37.760 align:middle line:90%
does the brain give to it?

00:46:37.760 --> 00:46:39.189 align:middle line:90%
So yes.

00:46:39.189 --> 00:46:40.980 align:middle line:84%
We haven't actually
gotten rid of the pain.

00:46:40.980 --> 00:46:43.180 align:middle line:84%
The pain signal is coming
up loud and clear, right?

00:46:43.180 --> 00:46:43.762 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:46:43.762 --> 00:46:45.970 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: It's just, how
does the brain deal with it?

00:46:45.970 --> 00:46:49.170 align:middle line:84%
And so you might
say in that sense

00:46:49.170 --> 00:46:51.610 align:middle line:84%
we haven't dealt
with the pain at all.

00:46:51.610 --> 00:46:54.480 align:middle line:84%
What we have dealt
with is your sense

00:46:54.480 --> 00:46:57.050 align:middle line:84%
of pain-- your sense
of victimization--

00:46:57.050 --> 00:46:59.170 align:middle line:84%
that we've given
you-- hopefully,

00:46:59.170 --> 00:47:02.330 align:middle line:84%
if we succeed--
mastery over the pain.

00:47:02.330 --> 00:47:03.441 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Fascinating.

00:47:03.441 --> 00:47:03.940 align:middle line:90%
Wow.

00:47:03.940 --> 00:47:05.160 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: The pain still exists.

00:47:05.160 --> 00:47:05.370 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Of course.

00:47:05.370 --> 00:47:06.840 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: And so
if you inquire, it

00:47:06.840 --> 00:47:09.660 align:middle line:84%
says yes, my foot still
hurts or my back still

00:47:09.660 --> 00:47:14.510 align:middle line:84%
hurts or whatever, but
it doesn't bother me.

00:47:14.510 --> 00:47:17.247 align:middle line:84%
Because the mind
has-- now the brain--

00:47:17.247 --> 00:47:17.830 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:47:17.830 --> 00:47:19.920 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: The mind
brain-- the brain mind

00:47:19.920 --> 00:47:22.290 align:middle line:90%
has risen above that pain.

00:47:22.290 --> 00:47:24.010 align:middle line:84%
So that is our hope
with chronic pain.

00:47:24.010 --> 00:47:27.890 align:middle line:84%
It's not to expunge it,
because that, indeed,

00:47:27.890 --> 00:47:30.989 align:middle line:90%
is not possible for us.

00:47:30.989 --> 00:47:32.530 align:middle line:84%
I mean, sometimes
we get rid of pain,

00:47:32.530 --> 00:47:34.450 align:middle line:84%
but in these extreme
cases of chronic pain,

00:47:34.450 --> 00:47:35.980 align:middle line:90%
no, we don't get rid of it.

00:47:35.980 --> 00:47:40.310 align:middle line:84%
But mastery of the pain,
it may still be possible.

00:47:40.310 --> 00:47:42.460 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: What I discovered
through the brain trauma

00:47:42.460 --> 00:47:46.130 align:middle line:84%
that I had was it took me about
20 sessions to get my brain

00:47:46.130 --> 00:47:50.450 align:middle line:84%
to feed back the
correct signal strength

00:47:50.450 --> 00:47:52.190 align:middle line:90%
than the rest of the brain was.

00:47:52.190 --> 00:47:54.340 align:middle line:84%
So how long would
it take someone,

00:47:54.340 --> 00:47:55.830 align:middle line:90%
and does it last permanently?

00:47:55.830 --> 00:47:59.950 align:middle line:84%
In my case, I needed to go
back every year or two just

00:47:59.950 --> 00:48:02.700 align:middle line:84%
to check to see-- as you
would any type of check up--

00:48:02.700 --> 00:48:04.690 align:middle line:84%
if the signal is still
responding accurately.

00:48:04.690 --> 00:48:06.110 align:middle line:90%
Does this last?

00:48:06.110 --> 00:48:08.890 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: Well, with
some chronic pain cases,

00:48:08.890 --> 00:48:11.970 align:middle line:84%
we find that they actually
need to take the equipment home

00:48:11.970 --> 00:48:14.680 align:middle line:90%
and train every once in a while.

00:48:14.680 --> 00:48:16.425 align:middle line:84%
Some people with
chronic pain who

00:48:16.425 --> 00:48:19.100 align:middle line:84%
have real sleep issues,
which is common,

00:48:19.100 --> 00:48:20.720 align:middle line:90%
they may train every day.

00:48:20.720 --> 00:48:21.920 align:middle line:90%
But it's worth it, right?

00:48:21.920 --> 00:48:23.304 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:48:23.304 --> 00:48:24.720 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: If a
half hour session--

00:48:24.720 --> 00:48:25.030 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: The
alternative is-- yeah.

00:48:25.030 --> 00:48:27.446 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: --with the machine
can give you a night's sleep,

00:48:27.446 --> 00:48:30.280 align:middle line:84%
you're willing to pay that
price rather than staring

00:48:30.280 --> 00:48:32.150 align:middle line:84%
at the ceiling in
pain all night, right?

00:48:32.150 --> 00:48:32.650 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:48:32.650 --> 00:48:33.320 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:48:33.320 --> 00:48:36.380 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: And so we have
had people who've basically

00:48:36.380 --> 00:48:39.360 align:middle line:84%
been on a daily diet
of neurofeedback

00:48:39.360 --> 00:48:40.820 align:middle line:90%
just to manage their pain.

00:48:40.820 --> 00:48:42.880 align:middle line:84%
And they get hours of
pain free existence.

00:48:42.880 --> 00:48:46.960 align:middle line:84%
So we see phenomena all across
the map with chronic pain.

00:48:46.960 --> 00:48:50.170 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: What about with--
in the case of addictions

00:48:50.170 --> 00:48:52.599 align:middle line:84%
where those tend to take
over or control the mind?

00:48:52.599 --> 00:48:53.890 align:middle line:90%
Does this help with addictions?

00:48:53.890 --> 00:48:56.620 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: This is a huge story.

00:48:56.620 --> 00:49:00.006 align:middle line:84%
The addiction must be seen
as a brain based problem.

00:49:00.006 --> 00:49:01.880 align:middle line:84%
If it doesn't start as
a brain based problem,

00:49:01.880 --> 00:49:03.285 align:middle line:84%
it becomes a brain
based problem.

00:49:03.285 --> 00:49:03.670 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:49:03.670 --> 00:49:04.169 align:middle line:90%
Mm-hmm.

00:49:04.169 --> 00:49:06.130 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: And so it needs
a brain based remedy.

00:49:06.130 --> 00:49:09.850 align:middle line:84%
Whatever else is needed, it
also needs a brain based remedy.

00:49:09.850 --> 00:49:12.930 align:middle line:84%
And we do wonderfully
with addictions.

00:49:12.930 --> 00:49:15.010 align:middle line:84%
Again, we need to
train the brain out

00:49:15.010 --> 00:49:18.710 align:middle line:84%
of that state of
dependency on the drug.

00:49:18.710 --> 00:49:22.540 align:middle line:84%
And the fact that we succeed
is illustrated by the fact

00:49:22.540 --> 00:49:25.770 align:middle line:84%
that many people actually
even lose their craving.

00:49:25.770 --> 00:49:28.430 align:middle line:84%
Now, in the past, in
conventional treatments,

00:49:28.430 --> 00:49:31.290 align:middle line:84%
success constitutes just
being able to stay sober

00:49:31.290 --> 00:49:34.040 align:middle line:90%
and whatever-- not use.

00:49:34.040 --> 00:49:36.210 align:middle line:84%
But if you ask the person
would they prefer to use,

00:49:36.210 --> 00:49:37.530 align:middle line:90%
the answer is yes, right?

00:49:37.530 --> 00:49:38.030 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Ah.

00:49:38.030 --> 00:49:39.650 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: It's not like we've
overcome the addiction in that

00:49:39.650 --> 00:49:40.120 align:middle line:90%
sense--

00:49:40.120 --> 00:49:40.400 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:49:40.400 --> 00:49:41.441 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: --by and large.

00:49:41.441 --> 00:49:44.340 align:middle line:84%
So it's just that we've
given them the strength

00:49:44.340 --> 00:49:46.850 align:middle line:90%
to live a different life.

00:49:46.850 --> 00:49:48.680 align:middle line:84%
And now, that's a
success in a way.

00:49:48.680 --> 00:49:50.660 align:middle line:84%
But how much better
if we actually

00:49:50.660 --> 00:49:54.540 align:middle line:84%
get the person to the
point where he can say--

00:49:54.540 --> 00:49:55.060 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: No.

00:49:55.060 --> 00:49:56.440 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: --no, I
don't need the drug.

00:49:56.440 --> 00:49:56.800 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Mm-hmm.

00:49:56.800 --> 00:49:59.174 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: In fact, the drug
is no longer part of my life.

00:49:59.174 --> 00:50:01.037 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It no longer
has power over me.

00:50:01.037 --> 00:50:02.620 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: No longer
has power over me.

00:50:02.620 --> 00:50:05.040 align:middle line:84%
And you see, when the
brain wants the drug,

00:50:05.040 --> 00:50:07.040 align:middle line:90%
that's very hard to resist.

00:50:07.040 --> 00:50:08.710 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's a
chemical firing that--

00:50:08.710 --> 00:50:09.080 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Right.

00:50:09.080 --> 00:50:09.230 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:50:09.230 --> 00:50:11.270 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: And the brain
will have its way.

00:50:11.270 --> 00:50:12.777 align:middle line:90%
It's very hard to--

00:50:12.777 --> 00:50:13.610 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:50:13.610 --> 00:50:14.985 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: Willpower
is overrated.

00:50:14.985 --> 00:50:18.620 align:middle line:84%
If willpower is all you've
got, then be my guest.

00:50:18.620 --> 00:50:19.530 align:middle line:90%
Rely on it.

00:50:19.530 --> 00:50:20.760 align:middle line:90%
But it's not all we've got.

00:50:20.760 --> 00:50:21.990 align:middle line:90%
We can train the brain.

00:50:21.990 --> 00:50:22.490 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:50:22.490 --> 00:50:24.630 align:middle line:84%
That's why they say
willpower doesn't often work.

00:50:24.630 --> 00:50:25.296 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Right.

00:50:25.296 --> 00:50:29.300 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Because it is powerful
will, in the wrong direction

00:50:29.300 --> 00:50:29.800 align:middle line:90%
sometimes.

00:50:29.800 --> 00:50:31.341 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: Well, and
if we tell people

00:50:31.341 --> 00:50:34.660 align:middle line:84%
that they must depend on
willpower and then they fail,

00:50:34.660 --> 00:50:36.850 align:middle line:84%
then we've also given
them a sense of failure.

00:50:36.850 --> 00:50:39.530 align:middle line:84%
It says no, we need to give
people every opportunity

00:50:39.530 --> 00:50:41.480 align:middle line:84%
to succeed, and that
means brain training.

00:50:41.480 --> 00:50:43.021 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So this
could also have to do

00:50:43.021 --> 00:50:45.630 align:middle line:84%
with food addictions
and weight loss,

00:50:45.630 --> 00:50:48.180 align:middle line:84%
essentially, because
you stop the addiction

00:50:48.180 --> 00:50:50.167 align:middle line:90%
for certain foods or bad foods?

00:50:50.167 --> 00:50:51.000 align:middle line:90%
How would that work?

00:50:51.000 --> 00:50:51.625 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Yeah.

00:50:51.625 --> 00:50:55.730 align:middle line:84%
So appetite regulation is a
big part of the food issue--

00:50:55.730 --> 00:50:59.290 align:middle line:84%
just basically getting to
the point of just regulating

00:50:59.290 --> 00:51:00.310 align:middle line:90%
your appetite.

00:51:00.310 --> 00:51:03.700 align:middle line:84%
And so we have people, they
go to restaurant and say,

00:51:03.700 --> 00:51:07.950 align:middle line:84%
I actually didn't feel
like ordering dessert.

00:51:07.950 --> 00:51:08.710 align:middle line:90%
What happened?

00:51:08.710 --> 00:51:12.530 align:middle line:84%
Who is the person who
drove by the bakery

00:51:12.530 --> 00:51:15.550 align:middle line:84%
today without
stopping for donuts?

00:51:15.550 --> 00:51:17.930 align:middle line:84%
Who is the person that
passed up on desert?

00:51:17.930 --> 00:51:19.264 align:middle line:90%
They don't recognize themselves.

00:51:19.264 --> 00:51:20.929 align:middle line:84%
Their brain is now
in a different place.

00:51:20.929 --> 00:51:21.780 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:51:21.780 --> 00:51:23.697 align:middle line:84%
Although they still
observe, they don't crave.

00:51:23.697 --> 00:51:24.571 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: No, no, no.

00:51:24.571 --> 00:51:25.626 align:middle line:90%
It's not by willpower.

00:51:25.626 --> 00:51:27.500 align:middle line:84%
It's their brain is now
in a different place.

00:51:27.500 --> 00:51:29.310 align:middle line:84%
Their brain has
now appropriately

00:51:29.310 --> 00:51:31.340 align:middle line:90%
regulated appetite.

00:51:31.340 --> 00:51:33.700 align:middle line:84%
And now these things
become non issues.

00:51:33.700 --> 00:51:35.310 align:middle line:84%
The cravings disappear
and so forth.

00:51:35.310 --> 00:51:37.020 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: The signals go
into a different direction?

00:51:37.020 --> 00:51:37.730 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Yeah.

00:51:37.730 --> 00:51:41.220 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So those patterns or
those bundles actually break up

00:51:41.220 --> 00:51:43.534 align:middle line:84%
and new habits and
patterns and bundles form?

00:51:43.534 --> 00:51:44.200 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Right.

00:51:44.200 --> 00:51:46.320 align:middle line:84%
And since we're talking
about new habits,

00:51:46.320 --> 00:51:50.260 align:middle line:84%
yes, it may take awhile to get
those new habits consolidated.

00:51:50.260 --> 00:51:55.715 align:middle line:84%
So you may see a quick impact
such as not wanting desert--

00:51:55.715 --> 00:51:56.840 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: --in the beginning?

00:51:56.840 --> 00:51:57.490 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: --in the beginning.

00:51:57.490 --> 00:51:57.890 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:51:57.890 --> 00:51:59.640 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: But to
consolidate that and make

00:51:59.640 --> 00:52:01.767 align:middle line:84%
that a new habit, it's
still going to take a while.

00:52:01.767 --> 00:52:02.600 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: And lasting.

00:52:02.600 --> 00:52:02.920 align:middle line:90%
OK

00:52:02.920 --> 00:52:03.544 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Yeah.

00:52:03.544 --> 00:52:07.140 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Now once again
about the program,

00:52:07.140 --> 00:52:11.060 align:middle line:84%
the computer or--
say the technician

00:52:11.060 --> 00:52:15.480 align:middle line:84%
wants to help someone with
this appetite control.

00:52:15.480 --> 00:52:18.860 align:middle line:84%
So can you enter that type
of program into the computer?

00:52:18.860 --> 00:52:21.400 align:middle line:84%
Is that how that works from
the practitioner's perspective?

00:52:21.400 --> 00:52:22.769 align:middle line:90%
I'm just curious.

00:52:22.769 --> 00:52:23.560 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Well, OK.

00:52:23.560 --> 00:52:25.100 align:middle line:84%
Here, the brain is
in our favorite.

00:52:25.100 --> 00:52:28.080 align:middle line:84%
The brain functions as
an integrated whole.

00:52:28.080 --> 00:52:32.390 align:middle line:84%
It's amazing just how
intricately everything

00:52:32.390 --> 00:52:33.460 align:middle line:90%
is intertwined.

00:52:33.460 --> 00:52:36.670 align:middle line:84%
So it turns out we have
a very basic approach

00:52:36.670 --> 00:52:39.120 align:middle line:84%
that if your
problem is appetite,

00:52:39.120 --> 00:52:40.340 align:middle line:90%
it's going to help that.

00:52:40.340 --> 00:52:41.850 align:middle line:84%
And if your problem
is addiction,

00:52:41.850 --> 00:52:43.030 align:middle line:90%
it's going to help that.

00:52:43.030 --> 00:52:45.810 align:middle line:84%
But fundamentally,
it's one approach.

00:52:45.810 --> 00:52:47.050 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Hmm.

00:52:47.050 --> 00:52:49.660 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: So what happens is
there is individualization

00:52:49.660 --> 00:52:51.524 align:middle line:84%
of the training, but
it depends on how

00:52:51.524 --> 00:52:52.690 align:middle line:90%
you respond to the training.

00:52:52.690 --> 00:52:55.530 align:middle line:84%
And then the training
will differentiate

00:52:55.530 --> 00:52:58.450 align:middle line:84%
in these different ways,
but it'll differentiate not

00:52:58.450 --> 00:53:01.960 align:middle line:84%
according to whether you have
migraines or night terrors

00:53:01.960 --> 00:53:02.780 align:middle line:90%
or whatever.

00:53:02.780 --> 00:53:05.770 align:middle line:84%
It'll differentiate according
to who you are as a person.

00:53:05.770 --> 00:53:08.830 align:middle line:90%


00:53:08.830 --> 00:53:11.360 align:middle line:84%
And it will go according to
the character of your brain,

00:53:11.360 --> 00:53:14.170 align:middle line:84%
not just depending
on what is failing.

00:53:14.170 --> 00:53:17.910 align:middle line:84%
So it's that kind of
individualization.

00:53:17.910 --> 00:53:20.640 align:middle line:84%
So this becomes very
personalized training.

00:53:20.640 --> 00:53:22.820 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Tell me a little
bit about migraines.

00:53:22.820 --> 00:53:24.200 align:middle line:90%
You just mentioned migraines.

00:53:24.200 --> 00:53:26.872 align:middle line:90%
Could this help with migraines?

00:53:26.872 --> 00:53:27.830 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Very much so.

00:53:27.830 --> 00:53:32.670 align:middle line:84%
In fact, if I were to list the
conditions in-- rank ordered

00:53:32.670 --> 00:53:34.400 align:middle line:84%
according to how
well we do with them,

00:53:34.400 --> 00:53:36.960 align:middle line:84%
migraines would be
just about at the top.

00:53:36.960 --> 00:53:41.770 align:middle line:84%
And people really need to know
this because a lot of people

00:53:41.770 --> 00:53:45.980 align:middle line:84%
are sort of content to live with
a certain level of migraines

00:53:45.980 --> 00:53:48.150 align:middle line:84%
in their lives and
they accept that.

00:53:48.150 --> 00:53:50.420 align:middle line:84%
Well, as horrible
as migraines are,

00:53:50.420 --> 00:53:52.220 align:middle line:84%
I would not find
that acceptable.

00:53:52.220 --> 00:53:54.860 align:middle line:84%
These people need to know
that there's an alternative.

00:53:54.860 --> 00:53:57.561 align:middle line:84%
And now, we tend to see the more
difficult end of the spectrum--

00:53:57.561 --> 00:53:59.685 align:middle line:84%
people who have spent 10
to 30 years with migraines

00:53:59.685 --> 00:54:01.980 align:middle line:84%
and they're just tired
of it and whatever

00:54:01.980 --> 00:54:03.810 align:middle line:84%
and they're happy
to find this remedy.

00:54:03.810 --> 00:54:06.380 align:middle line:90%


00:54:06.380 --> 00:54:08.730 align:middle line:84%
And so we know we
can succeed even

00:54:08.730 --> 00:54:11.570 align:middle line:84%
with the most intractable
cases of migraine, which

00:54:11.570 --> 00:54:15.150 align:middle line:84%
means the easier
part of the spectrum

00:54:15.150 --> 00:54:16.917 align:middle line:90%
should be easier to deal with.

00:54:16.917 --> 00:54:17.750 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:54:17.750 --> 00:54:21.320 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: We even had
a case of a person who

00:54:21.320 --> 00:54:24.580 align:middle line:84%
had a multi-decadal year
history of migraines.

00:54:24.580 --> 00:54:27.625 align:middle line:84%
And from the first session on,
never had another migraine.

00:54:27.625 --> 00:54:28.250 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Really?

00:54:28.250 --> 00:54:29.666 align:middle line:84%
I was going to ask
you how long it

00:54:29.666 --> 00:54:31.171 align:middle line:90%
takes for that to be effective.

00:54:31.171 --> 00:54:32.670 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: Well, it
made a difference

00:54:32.670 --> 00:54:33.753 align:middle line:90%
from the first session on.

00:54:33.753 --> 00:54:35.290 align:middle line:84%
Now, she still
needed 40 sessions

00:54:35.290 --> 00:54:37.090 align:middle line:90%
to consolidate the training.

00:54:37.090 --> 00:54:37.636 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh.

00:54:37.636 --> 00:54:38.310 align:middle line:90%
Oh, I see.

00:54:38.310 --> 00:54:38.730 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Right.

00:54:38.730 --> 00:54:40.550 align:middle line:84%
It's not like, OK, one
session, we're done.

00:54:40.550 --> 00:54:41.230 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:54:41.230 --> 00:54:42.850 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: She still
had 40 sessions.

00:54:42.850 --> 00:54:46.577 align:middle line:84%
But never in that time did
she have another migraine.

00:54:46.577 --> 00:54:47.410 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:54:47.410 --> 00:54:49.990 align:middle line:84%
So what does something
like this cost?

00:54:49.990 --> 00:54:52.170 align:middle line:90%
Does insurance cover it?

00:54:52.170 --> 00:54:53.420 align:middle line:90%
How does it work?

00:54:53.420 --> 00:54:56.050 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: Insurance is
getting-- is getting better,

00:54:56.050 --> 00:54:58.440 align:middle line:84%
but insurance is
oriented towards saying

00:54:58.440 --> 00:54:59.890 align:middle line:90%
no, and so forth.

00:54:59.890 --> 00:55:02.740 align:middle line:84%
And this is going to take a
while before the insurance

00:55:02.740 --> 00:55:06.040 align:middle line:84%
realizes that we really
solve people's problems

00:55:06.040 --> 00:55:08.180 align:middle line:90%
and it's really cost effective.

00:55:08.180 --> 00:55:10.970 align:middle line:84%
It's more cost effective
to solve people's problems

00:55:10.970 --> 00:55:12.400 align:middle line:90%
than to keep saying no.

00:55:12.400 --> 00:55:15.460 align:middle line:84%
Because what happens is
in the course of life,

00:55:15.460 --> 00:55:19.610 align:middle line:84%
with what we call dysregulation,
what we're dealing with here

00:55:19.610 --> 00:55:20.960 align:middle line:90%
just gets worse.

00:55:20.960 --> 00:55:23.520 align:middle line:84%
And pretty soon, you're dealing
with serious medical issues.

00:55:23.520 --> 00:55:26.420 align:middle line:84%
Whereas if you had taken care
of the problem of dysregulation

00:55:26.420 --> 00:55:27.510 align:middle line:90%
when it was manageable--

00:55:27.510 --> 00:55:28.880 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Ah, I see.

00:55:28.880 --> 00:55:31.620 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: --then the
entire trajectory

00:55:31.620 --> 00:55:35.740 align:middle line:84%
in life-- across life, this
lifespan would've been better.

00:55:35.740 --> 00:55:37.615 align:middle line:90%
So I don't--

00:55:37.615 --> 00:55:39.240 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You can still
affect it if it's

00:55:39.240 --> 00:55:41.448 align:middle line:84%
in a chronic stage-- you
can still make a difference?

00:55:41.448 --> 00:55:42.180 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Yeah.

00:55:42.180 --> 00:55:43.110 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And are
there measures being

00:55:43.110 --> 00:55:45.210 align:middle line:84%
made towards getting the
insurance companies more

00:55:45.210 --> 00:55:45.790 align:middle line:90%
onboarded?

00:55:45.790 --> 00:55:49.720 align:middle line:84%
Some of them do cover it
under mental health, right?

00:55:49.720 --> 00:55:53.680 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: We've not made
insurance companies a priority.

00:55:53.680 --> 00:55:55.140 align:middle line:84%
And perhaps the
time is coming when

00:55:55.140 --> 00:55:58.890 align:middle line:84%
they should be brought
into the picture.

00:55:58.890 --> 00:56:02.060 align:middle line:84%
Because they've taken,
historically, such an

00:56:02.060 --> 00:56:04.910 align:middle line:90%
anti position.

00:56:04.910 --> 00:56:06.910 align:middle line:84%
But I think the
times are changing.

00:56:06.910 --> 00:56:10.040 align:middle line:84%
And the time is coming
when-- it has happened

00:56:10.040 --> 00:56:12.020 align:middle line:84%
which insurance companies
and hospitals and so

00:56:12.020 --> 00:56:14.547 align:middle line:90%
forth are approaching us.

00:56:14.547 --> 00:56:15.380 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's good.

00:56:15.380 --> 00:56:15.980 align:middle line:90%
That's very good.

00:56:15.980 --> 00:56:16.070 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Yeah.

00:56:16.070 --> 00:56:16.380 align:middle line:90%
That's good news.

00:56:16.380 --> 00:56:16.440 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Very helpful.

00:56:16.440 --> 00:56:18.950 align:middle line:84%
Now, you have a new book
out called "Brian's Legacy."

00:56:18.950 --> 00:56:21.360 align:middle line:84%
And this is the story
of your son, yes?

00:56:21.360 --> 00:56:24.970 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: This is the story
of our son's struggles

00:56:24.970 --> 00:56:26.430 align:middle line:90%
with his epilepsy.

00:56:26.430 --> 00:56:30.530 align:middle line:84%
And it's remarkable in the
sense that most of the book

00:56:30.530 --> 00:56:32.320 align:middle line:84%
is actually his story
in his own words.

00:56:32.320 --> 00:56:33.294 align:middle line:90%
It's his own journal.

00:56:33.294 --> 00:56:33.960 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, wow.

00:56:33.960 --> 00:56:37.670 align:middle line:84%
>>OTHMER: It's his college
years in which he describes

00:56:37.670 --> 00:56:39.610 align:middle line:84%
how he relates to
his own conditions--

00:56:39.610 --> 00:56:42.910 align:middle line:84%
his own increasing
mastery of his condition.

00:56:42.910 --> 00:56:47.770 align:middle line:84%
Now, ultimately, we lost him
in his senior year of college.

00:56:47.770 --> 00:56:53.150 align:middle line:84%
So ultimately, we never finally
got the seizures under control,

00:56:53.150 --> 00:56:55.610 align:middle line:84%
despite the medications,
despite the neurofeedback.

00:56:55.610 --> 00:56:57.660 align:middle line:84%
He was still
wrestling with that.

00:56:57.660 --> 00:57:00.620 align:middle line:84%
But as a person, he
really developed,

00:57:00.620 --> 00:57:02.740 align:middle line:84%
and that was mainly
with the neurofeedback.

00:57:02.740 --> 00:57:04.940 align:middle line:84%
And so that story
is-- so I would--

00:57:04.940 --> 00:57:06.800 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So his quality
of life was better?

00:57:06.800 --> 00:57:07.340 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Oh, yeah, yeah.

00:57:07.340 --> 00:57:08.964 align:middle line:84%
It really made a
human being out of him

00:57:08.964 --> 00:57:12.577 align:middle line:84%
to where he could
make friends and was

00:57:12.577 --> 00:57:13.910 align:middle line:90%
great to live with and so forth.

00:57:13.910 --> 00:57:17.910 align:middle line:84%
But the book, I think, is to
be particularly recommended

00:57:17.910 --> 00:57:24.242 align:middle line:84%
to parents who are dealing
with their own problem children

00:57:24.242 --> 00:57:27.750 align:middle line:84%
or who've had their own
difficulties growing up,

00:57:27.750 --> 00:57:29.210 align:middle line:90%
of this kind.

00:57:29.210 --> 00:57:32.610 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Just to talk about
the solution oriented approach

00:57:32.610 --> 00:57:34.367 align:middle line:90%
to EEG.

00:57:34.367 --> 00:57:34.950 align:middle line:90%
>>OTHMER: Yes.

00:57:34.950 --> 00:57:39.160 align:middle line:84%
And now it looks like-- we call
it "Brian's Legacy" because we

00:57:39.160 --> 00:57:43.880 align:middle line:84%
feel like Brian got
us into the field.

00:57:43.880 --> 00:57:46.910 align:middle line:84%
And now it looks like
we're heading to the point

00:57:46.910 --> 00:57:51.050 align:middle line:84%
where the self-regulation
technologies will play--

00:57:51.050 --> 00:57:54.980 align:middle line:84%
in the future-- play a major
role in bending the cost

00:57:54.980 --> 00:57:58.530 align:middle line:84%
curve of medicine,
and also just simply

00:57:58.530 --> 00:57:59.950 align:middle line:90%
improving the quality of life.

00:57:59.950 --> 00:58:02.500 align:middle line:84%
There's so much suffering in
the world which is unnecessary.

00:58:02.500 --> 00:58:02.702 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:58:02.702 --> 00:58:03.202 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:58:03.202 --> 00:58:05.460 align:middle line:84%
Well, we've talked
about everything

00:58:05.460 --> 00:58:10.250 align:middle line:84%
from the ADD, ADHD
to appetite control.

00:58:10.250 --> 00:58:12.570 align:middle line:84%
We haven't even touched on
peak performance and memory

00:58:12.570 --> 00:58:15.300 align:middle line:84%
and focus, because it also
helps with that, as well.

00:58:15.300 --> 00:58:17.710 align:middle line:84%
There's so many things
that EEG and neurofeedback

00:58:17.710 --> 00:58:18.300 align:middle line:90%
can help with.

00:58:18.300 --> 00:58:19.890 align:middle line:84%
And I'm really glad
that you're here

00:58:19.890 --> 00:58:22.120 align:middle line:84%
to explain it, to
demonstrate it,

00:58:22.120 --> 00:58:23.920 align:middle line:84%
to show us how
the program works,

00:58:23.920 --> 00:58:27.520 align:middle line:84%
and to show that it's such a
solution for so many things.

00:58:27.520 --> 00:58:30.240 align:middle line:84%
So thanks for exposing
us to this world.

00:58:30.240 --> 00:58:30.990 align:middle line:90%
I appreciate it.

